						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">dougeff wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It was going to be more subtle...<br /><br />The ninja is rescuing his 'girlfriend', if he took off his mask and revealed to really be a woman, I was going to leave it to the imagination what 'girlfriend' means.</div><br /><br />I think that's often the best way to do it. Ambiguity leaves room for people not to be offended in any direction and still lets you show what you want to. One of my favorite things about Shovel Knight is the open-endedness of the player's relation to Shield Knight. Hell, you don't even know who Shovel Knight is under the armor.<br />...which is also why the gender swap mode was a really bad idea on Yacht Club's part.<br />Anyways, I find that most of the time the sexuality (sexual identity? gender identity? I'm not up to date here) of a given character in a given game doesn't ever come into question. If the sexuality is ever brought up unprovokedly it can leave a sour taste in the player's mouth whether he's bigoted or not. See Borderlands.</div>

